content:
A Calculation Procedure is a series of calculations performed using matrix lookups and user-defined variables and constants. A calculation procedure can call Apex classes for pre- and post-calculation custom logic. Calculation procedures are part of pricing rules.

There are two types of calculation procedures:

Class-based: Pricing logic is written in an Apex class.

Declarative: Pricing logic is implemented using matrix lookups, variables, constants, and basic math operations.

A declarative calculation procedure can use Data Mappers to read and save data from Salesforce objects. Each step in a Calculation Procedure can have a condition that must be met in order for the step to be executed. 

You can specify the UnitPrice variable as output. The output from a calculation step can be included in the final output by selecting Include in output.

To use Apex to define pricing logic, create a class-based Calculation Procedure. To clone a calculation procedure, you're cloning all of its versions, steps, variables, and constants. Variables, constants, and matrices must be created before they can be used in a Calculation Procedure.

For each step in the Calculation Procedure, you can define a condition that must be met in order for the step to be executed. The following functions are supported in calculation procedures:

Calculation Procedures Overview

There are two types of steps: Matrix and Formula.

Each type has specific characteristics such as the ability to include output from a calculation step in the final output by selecting Include in output.
title: Understanding Calculation Procedures
